# 16. Information Gathering Methodology

Information gathering establishes the technical baseline for all subsequent assessment activities.

The assessment team shall collect sufficient information to understand:

* Firewall architecture
* Security design
* Administrative model
* Business dependencies
* Existing security controls
* Network segmentation
* Change management practices
* Operational processes

The objective is to eliminate assumptions before technical validation begins.

---

## 16.1 Information Sources

Information may be obtained from:

* Configuration exports
* Firewall backups
* Running configurations
* Network topology diagrams
* High Availability designs
* Change records
* Security policies
* Standard operating procedures
* Incident records
* Asset inventories
* Risk registers
* Architecture documentation
* Administrative interviews
* API responses
* CLI output
* Vendor management platforms

Multiple independent information sources should be used wherever possible.

---

## 16.2 Information Validation

Collected information shall be validated before use.

Validation methods include:

* Cross-referencing multiple sources
* Configuration comparison
* Live verification
* Administrative confirmation
* Timestamp validation
* Version verification
* Asset ownership verification

Unverified information shall not be used to support findings.

---

# 17. Architecture Review Methodology

The architecture review evaluates whether the firewall deployment supports secure enterprise network design.

The review shall examine:

* Firewall placement
* Trust boundaries
* Security zones
* Segmentation strategy
* Routing architecture
* Internet edge design
* DMZ implementation
* East-West traffic controls
* North-South traffic controls
* Cloud connectivity
* Third-party connectivity
* Remote access architecture
* High Availability topology
* Administrative architecture

---

## 17.1 Assessment Objectives

The architecture review shall determine whether:

* Security controls align with business requirements.
* Network segmentation supports least privilege.
* Trust boundaries are clearly defined.
* Firewall placement minimizes attack surface.
* Critical assets receive appropriate protection.
* Redundancy requirements are met.
* Single points of failure are minimized.

---

## 17.2 Validation Activities

Assessors shall validate:

* Logical diagrams
* Physical topology
* Routing paths
* Interface assignments
* Security zones
* Network objects
* Virtual systems
* VRFs
* Cloud networking constructs
* Redundant paths

Observed architecture shall be compared against documented designs.

---

# 18. Management Plane Review Methodology

The management plane assessment evaluates the security of administrative access and operational management.

The review shall cover:

* Administrative interfaces
* Authentication mechanisms
* Authorization controls
* Identity integration
* Administrative roles
* MFA implementation
* Remote management
* Local accounts
* Password policy
* API security
* Certificate management
* Management encryption
* Session controls
* Administrative logging

---

## 18.1 Assessment Objectives

The assessment shall determine whether:

* Administrative access is appropriately restricted.
* Authentication mechanisms are secure.
* Privileged access follows least privilege.
* Administrative activities are auditable.
* Management interfaces are protected.
* Legacy management protocols have been eliminated.
* Administrative exposure is minimized.

---

## 18.2 Validation Activities

Assessors should validate:

* HTTPS configuration
* SSH configuration
* TLS settings
* Administrative ACLs
* MFA configuration
* AAA integration
* RADIUS integration
* TACACS+ integration
* LDAP integration
* SAML/OIDC integration where applicable
* Idle timeout configuration
* Login banners
* Account lockout settings
* Certificate validity
* API authentication
* Administrative audit logs

---

# 19. Rule Base Review Methodology

The firewall rule base represents the organization's primary traffic enforcement mechanism.

Its assessment shall evaluate both security effectiveness and operational quality.

---

## 19.1 Assessment Objectives

The review shall determine whether firewall policies:

* Enforce business requirements.
* Minimize attack surface.
* Follow least privilege.
* Prevent unauthorized communication.
* Maintain operational consistency.
* Reduce policy complexity.
* Support regulatory requirements.

---

## 19.2 Rule Validation Areas

Assessors shall evaluate:

* Rule ordering
* Rule optimization
* Rule shadowing
* Rule redundancy
* Duplicate rules
* Expired rules
* Disabled rules
* Temporary rules
* Broad permit rules
* Any-to-any policies
* Service definitions
* Application controls
* User-based policies
* Time-based rules
* Security profiles
* Logging configuration
* Cleanup rules
* Implicit deny behavior

---

## 19.3 Rule Analysis Methodology

Each rule should be evaluated for:

* Business justification
* Risk exposure
* Rule usage
* Traffic volume
* Administrative ownership
* Review history
* Expiration status
* Compliance impact
* Logging effectiveness
* Threat exposure

No rule should be considered secure solely because it functions correctly.

---

# 20. NAT Review Methodology

Network Address Translation shall be assessed as a critical security function.

The review shall evaluate:

* Source NAT
* Destination NAT
* Static NAT
* Dynamic NAT
* PAT
* NAT exemptions
* Hairpin NAT
* VIP objects
* Port forwarding
* NAT ordering
* Overlapping translations

---

## 20.1 Assessment Objectives

The review shall determine whether:

* Address translations support security objectives.
* NAT policies do not bypass inspection.
* Translation rules minimize exposure.
* Public services are appropriately restricted.
* Administrative consistency is maintained.

---

## 20.2 Validation Activities

Assessors shall review:

* Translation logic
* Object definitions
* Public IP exposure
* Service mappings
* Internet-facing assets
* DMZ exposure
* Internal segmentation
* Cloud NAT
* IPv6 translation
* Routing interaction

---

# 21. VPN Review Methodology

Virtual Private Network services provide secure connectivity between trusted endpoints.

The assessment shall evaluate:

* Site-to-site VPN
* Remote access VPN
* Clientless VPN
* Cloud VPN
* SD-WAN VPN
* IPsec
* SSL/TLS VPN
* Authentication methods
* Encryption standards
* Key management
* Certificate usage
* Split tunneling
* Routing controls

---

## 21.1 Assessment Objectives

The review shall determine whether:

* VPN services use approved cryptographic standards.
* Authentication mechanisms are secure.
* Tunnel permissions follow least privilege.
* Remote access is appropriately restricted.
* Cryptographic lifecycles are managed.
* VPN monitoring supports incident response.

---

## 21.2 Validation Activities

Assessors shall review:

* IKE configuration
* Phase 1 policies
* Phase 2 policies
* Cipher suites
* Perfect Forward Secrecy
* Certificate validity
* Key rotation
* User authentication
* MFA enforcement
* Tunnel monitoring
* Failover behavior
* VPN logging

---

# 22. Logging & Monitoring Review Methodology

Logging provides the foundation for visibility, incident detection, forensic investigation, and regulatory compliance.

The assessment shall evaluate:

* Logging coverage
* Event quality
* Time synchronization
* Log retention
* SIEM integration
* Alerting mechanisms
* Administrative logging
* Threat logging
* VPN logging
* Configuration change logging
* Audit trail completeness

---

## 22.1 Assessment Objectives

The review shall determine whether:

* Critical events are logged.
* Logs are protected from tampering.
* Monitoring supports rapid detection.
* Log retention satisfies policy and regulatory requirements.
* Security teams receive actionable alerts.
* Administrative accountability is preserved.

---

## 22.2 Validation Activities

Assessors shall verify:

