# 25. Evidence Collection Methodology

Evidence forms the foundation of every EFSAF assessment. No observation, finding, conclusion, risk rating, or recommendation shall be issued without sufficient supporting evidence.

Evidence shall be collected in accordance with **EFSAF-EVD-001** and maintained throughout the assessment lifecycle.

The assessment team shall ensure that evidence is:

* Accurate
* Complete
* Verifiable
* Relevant
* Timely
* Repeatable
* Traceable
* Securely stored
* Protected against unauthorized modification

The burden of proof shall always rest with the assessor.

---

# 26. Evidence Classification

Evidence shall be classified to ensure consistency in evaluation and reporting.

| Evidence Class | Description                                                        | Examples                                                          |
| -------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------ | ----------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Primary        | Direct technical evidence collected from the target environment    | Running configuration, CLI output, API responses, packet captures |
| Secondary      | Supporting documentation that corroborates primary evidence        | Architecture diagrams, SOPs, change requests                      |
| Tertiary       | Contextual information obtained through interviews or observations | Administrator interviews, operational demonstrations              |

Primary evidence shall take precedence over all other evidence types.

---

# 27. Evidence Sources

Evidence may be obtained from, but is not limited to:

* Firewall configuration exports
* Running configuration snapshots
* Command-line interface (CLI) output
* REST API responses
* Central management platforms
* High Availability status information
* System event logs
* Security logs
* Audit logs
* Configuration backup files
* Packet captures
* Network flow records
* Authentication servers
* Directory services
* SIEM platforms
* Change management systems
* Asset inventories
* Vulnerability management platforms
* Configuration management databases (CMDB)
* Administrator interviews
* Security policy documentation

Multiple independent evidence sources should be used wherever practical.

---

# 28. Evidence Collection Workflow

The evidence collection process shall follow a standardized workflow.

```text
Identify Required Evidence
          │
          ▼
Collect Technical Data
          │
          ▼
Validate Authenticity
          │
          ▼
Normalize Evidence
          │
          ▼
Classify Evidence
          │
          ▼
Store Securely
          │
          ▼
Map to Assessment Controls
          │
          ▼
Reference in Findings
```

Each stage shall be completed before evidence is used to support assessment conclusions.

---

# 29. Evidence Integrity

Evidence integrity shall be maintained throughout the assessment.

Assessment teams shall ensure:

* Evidence remains unaltered after collection.
* Collection timestamps are preserved.
* Source systems are identified.
* Collection methods are documented.
* File integrity is maintained.
* Access is restricted to authorized personnel.
* Sensitive information is protected.

Where feasible, cryptographic hashing should be used to verify evidence integrity.

---

# 30. Evidence Traceability

Every finding shall be traceable back to supporting evidence.

The following traceability chain shall be maintained:

```text
Assessment Control
        │
        ▼
Assessment Activity
        │
        ▼
Collected Evidence
        │
        ▼
Technical Observation
        │
        ▼
Assessment Finding
        │
        ▼
Risk Rating
        │
        ▼
Recommendation
        │
        ▼
Final Report
```

No break in the traceability chain shall be permitted.

---

# 31. Finding Development Methodology

A finding represents a validated condition that may impact the confidentiality, integrity, availability, governance, or operational resilience of the firewall environment.

Findings shall be:

* Objective
* Evidence-based
* Technically accurate
* Risk-oriented
* Actionable
* Clearly written
* Vendor-neutral
* Business-relevant

---

## 31.1 Mandatory Finding Structure

Every finding shall include the following components:

* Finding Identifier
* Title
* Category
* Severity
* Risk Rating
* Affected Assets
* Description
* Technical Details
* Supporting Evidence
* Business Impact
* Likelihood
* Risk Analysis
* Compliance Impact
* Root Cause
* Recommendation
* Reference Standards
* Validation Status

This structure shall align with **EFSAF-TMP-001**.

---

# 32. Root Cause Analysis

Each finding shall identify the underlying cause rather than only the observed symptom.

Typical root cause categories include:

* Design weakness
* Configuration error
* Operational deficiency
* Process failure
* Governance weakness
* Documentation deficiency
* Monitoring gap
* Human error
* Technology limitation
* Vendor default configuration
* Inadequate change management
* Insufficient security awareness

Root cause analysis shall support long-term remediation rather than temporary correction.

---

# 33. Risk Evaluation Methodology

Risk evaluation shall follow the methodology defined in **EFSAF-RISK-001**.

The objective is to determine the business significance of each validated finding.

Risk evaluation shall consider:

* Threat capability
* Threat likelihood
* Exposure
* Existing controls
* Exploitability
* Business criticality
* Asset sensitivity
* Detection capability
* Recovery capability
* Regulatory implications
* Operational impact

Risk ratings shall not be assigned solely on technical severity.

---

## 33.1 Risk Evaluation Workflow

```text
Validated Finding
        │
        ▼
Threat Identification
        │
        ▼
Likelihood Assessment
        │
        ▼
Impact Assessment
        │
        ▼
Control Effectiveness Review
        │
        ▼
Residual Risk Calculation
        │
        ▼
Risk Classification
```

Residual risk shall be documented for every finding.

---

# 34. Risk Acceptance

Where remediation is not immediately feasible, formal risk acceptance may be considered.

Risk acceptance shall require:

* Business justification
* Risk owner approval
* Defined acceptance period
* Compensating controls
* Executive authorization
* Review schedule

Accepted risks shall remain visible within the assessment report and shall not be omitted from scoring calculations unless explicitly defined by organizational policy.

---

# 35. Compliance Validation Methodology

Compliance validation determines whether firewall controls satisfy applicable regulatory, contractual, and organizational requirements.

Compliance assessment shall complement—not replace—technical security evaluation.

---

## 35.1 Compliance Sources

Compliance validation may include:

* ISO/IEC 27001
* NIST Cybersecurity Framework
* CIS Controls
* PCI DSS
* SOC 2
* HIPAA
* GDPR
* Local regulatory requirements
* Internal enterprise policies
* Customer contractual obligations

Mappings shall be maintained using **EFSAF-MAP-001**.

---

## 35.2 Compliance Validation Workflow

```text
Identify Applicable Requirement
           │
           ▼
Map EFSAF Control
           │
           ▼
Validate Evidence
           │
           ▼
Determine Compliance Status
           │
           ▼
Document Gap
           │
           ▼
Record Supporting Evidence
```

Compliance conclusions shall always be evidence-based.

---

# 36. Security Scoring Methodology

Overall assessment scoring shall follow **EFSAF-SCORE-001**.

Scoring shall provide a quantitative representation of the assessed firewall security posture.

Scores shall support:

* Executive reporting
* Trend analysis
* Benchmarking
* Maturity measurement
* Program improvement

Scores shall not replace technical findings or risk evaluations.

---

## 36.1 Scoring Principles

Security scoring shall be:

* Objective
* Repeatable
* Transparent
* Evidence-based
* Risk-aware
* Defensible

The scoring process shall remain independent of organizational or vendor bias.

---

## 36.2 Scoring Workflow

```text
Validated Controls
         │
         ▼
Control Weighting
         │
         ▼
Risk Adjustment
         │
         ▼
Domain Scoring
         │
         ▼
Overall Security Score
         │
         ▼
Maturity Determination
```

