# 42. Report Structure

Every EFSAF assessment report shall contain, at a minimum:

1. Document Control
2. Version History
3. Classification
4. Distribution List
5. Executive Summary
6. Assessment Overview
7. Assessment Objectives
8. Scope
9. Methodology
10. Assessment Limitations
11. Assessment Team
12. Asset Inventory
13. Security Architecture Overview
14. Overall Security Score
15. Risk Summary
16. Compliance Summary
17. Detailed Findings
18. Recommendations
19. Security Maturity Assessment
20. Conclusion
21. Appendices
22. Evidence References
23. Glossary
24. Assessment Approval

The report structure shall remain consistent across all EFSAF assessments.

---

# 43. Executive Reporting Methodology

Executive reporting shall communicate the organization's security posture in a concise, business-focused manner.

The Executive Summary shall include:

* Overall security posture
* Overall security score
* Overall maturity level
* Number of findings by severity
* Highest business risks
* Critical assets affected
* Compliance status
* Strategic recommendations
* Remediation priorities
* Executive conclusion

Technical implementation details should not dominate executive reporting.

---

# 44. Technical Reporting Methodology

Technical reporting shall provide sufficient detail to enable remediation, validation, and future reassessment.

Each technical finding shall include:

* Unique identifier
* Technical description
* Evidence references
* Configuration excerpts
* Screenshots (where applicable)
* Risk analysis
* Compliance mapping
* Root cause
* Remediation guidance
* Validation status

Technical reports shall enable independent verification by another qualified assessor.

---

# 45. Peer Review Process

Every EFSAF assessment shall undergo independent peer review before release.

The peer reviewer shall not have primary responsibility for the assessment being reviewed.

The peer review shall evaluate:

* Technical accuracy
* Methodology compliance
* Evidence sufficiency
* Risk consistency
* Compliance mappings
* Security scoring
* Report quality
* Writing clarity
* Traceability
* Recommendation quality

Peer review comments shall be documented and resolved before report approval.

---

# 46. Independent Quality Assurance (QA)

Quality Assurance ensures that every EFSAF assessment meets enterprise consulting standards.

The QA reviewer shall verify:

* Adherence to EFSAF methodology
* Alignment with EFSAF standards
* Consistency of terminology
* Completeness of documentation
* Integrity of evidence references
* Consistency of risk ratings
* Consistency of compliance mappings
* Accuracy of scoring
* Formatting compliance
* Overall report quality

QA reviewers shall remain independent of the assessment team wherever practicable.

---

## 46.1 QA Validation Checklist

The following minimum checks shall be completed:

| QA Area       | Validation Requirement               |
| ------------- | ------------------------------------ |
| Scope         | Matches approved Rules of Engagement |
| Evidence      | Complete, referenced, and verifiable |
| Findings      | Supported by validated evidence      |
| Risk          | Consistent with EFSAF-RISK-001       |
| Compliance    | Consistent with EFSAF-MAP-001        |
| Scoring       | Consistent with EFSAF-SCORE-001      |
| Reporting     | Consistent with EFSAF-REP-001        |
| Documentation | Consistent with EFSAF-STD-001        |

No report shall be released until mandatory QA checks have been completed.

---

# 47. Client Presentation Methodology

Assessment results shall be formally presented to authorized stakeholders.

The presentation shall include:

* Assessment objectives
* Scope
* Methodology
* Overall security posture
* Security maturity
* High-risk findings
* Compliance status
* Business impact
* Remediation priorities
* Recommended roadmap

Presentations should emphasize business risk before technical detail.

---

## 47.1 Findings Validation Meeting

A formal findings validation session should be conducted prior to report finalization.

The session shall:

* Confirm factual accuracy
* Resolve technical misunderstandings
* Validate business context
* Review compensating controls
* Confirm asset ownership
* Identify accepted risks
* Clarify remediation expectations

Validated findings shall form the basis of the final report.

---

# 48. Remediation Tracking

EFSAF assessments should support ongoing remediation activities.

Organizations should maintain a remediation register containing:

* Finding identifier
* Risk rating
* Asset owner
* Remediation owner
* Planned action
* Target completion date
* Current status
* Validation status
* Residual risk
* Closure date

Remediation tracking should continue until all applicable findings have been addressed or formally accepted.

---

# 49. Follow-Up Assessment Methodology

Follow-up assessments validate the effectiveness of remediation efforts.

Follow-up activities may include:

* Configuration review
* Evidence verification
* Control testing
* Compliance revalidation
* Risk reassessment
* Security score recalculation
* Maturity reassessment

Only verified remediation shall result in finding closure.

---

# 50. Assessment Closure

An assessment shall be considered complete only after all closure activities have been finalized.

Mandatory closure activities include:

* Final report approval
* Report delivery
* Evidence repository completion
* Risk register update
* Lessons learned documentation
* Engagement review
* Administrative closure
* Secure evidence retention
* Client acknowledgment

Assessment closure shall be formally documented.

---

# 51. Continuous Improvement Framework

EFSAF adopts a continuous improvement model to ensure long-term relevance and effectiveness.

Organizations should periodically review:

* Assessment quality
* Methodology effectiveness
* Emerging threats
* New firewall technologies
* Regulatory changes
* Lessons learned
* Assessor feedback
* Client feedback
* Industry best practices

Improvements shall be governed through formal version control.

